<div type="original">
<pb f="1r" n="1" xml:id="pb-orig-1r-1" facs="#zone-pb-1r-1"/><lb n="1" xml:id="l-1"/>
<ab>Amice Rappard</ab><lb n="2" xml:id="l-2"/>
<ab>Uw schrijven ontving <lb n="3" xml:id="l-3"/>ik zooeven – tot mijn verwondering<c type="kp">_</c>– <lb n="4" xml:id="l-4"/>Ge ontvangt het hierbij terug<c type="kp">_</c>–<anchor n="1" xml:id="note-o-1"/></ab><lb n="5" xml:id="l-5"/>
<ab rend="indent">Na groete</ab>
<vg:whiteline/><lb n="6" xml:id="l-6"/>
<ab>Vincent</ab>
<vg:whiteline/></div>
<div type="translation">
<pb f="1r" n="1" xml:id="pb-trans-1r-1" facs="#zone-pb-1r-1"/>
<ab>My dear friend <rs type="pers" key="1306">Rappard</rs></ab>
    <ab>I just received your letter — to my surprise. You hereby get it back.<anchor n="1" xml:id="note-t-1"/></ab>
<ab rend="indent">Sincerely,</ab>
<vg:whiteline/>
<ab>Vincent</ab></div>
<div type="notes">
<note n="1" xml:id="n-1" target="#note-t-1">
<ab>Van Gogh was very put out by <rs type="pers" key="1306">Van Rappard</rs>’s criticism in response to the lithograph of <hi rend="ital"><rs type="ill" key="2135">The potato eaters</rs></hi>. Returning a letter in this way was tantamount to ending the relationship. Van Gogh explained himself in more detail in <ref target="let514.xml">letter 514</ref>.</ab></note></div></body></text></TEI>
